column9: LUMINARY 116 was the Lunar Module AGC software flown on Apollo 12.
LM131 rev 1 was the Lunar Module AGC software flown on Apollo 13.
LUMINARY 178 was the Lunar Module AGC software flown on Apollo 14.
LUMINARY 210 was the Lunar Module AGC software flown on Apollo 15, Apollo 16, and Apollo 17.
ZERLINA was a branch of Lunar Module AGC software used for developing engineering concepts such as the Variable Guidance Period.

Early AGC programs had names that were typically related to the sun, and usually had the word "sun" explicitly in the name, as in SUNSPOT, SUNDIAL, SUNDISK, SUNDANCE, SUNBURST.  One wonders why name them after the sun rather than the moon?  NASA had a different concern, which was that nobody could remember which of these programs went in the CM and which in the LM.  So NASA requested that the CM program's name begin with "C" (as in COLOSSUS) and the LM program's name begin with "L" (as in LUMINARY).  After a few years, though, MIT/IL apparently forgot the rule and named the final CM program ARTEMIS.
COLOSSUS 237 was the Command Module AGC software flown on Apollo 8.
COLOSSUS 249 was the Command Module AGC software flown on Apollo 9.

column9: ARTEMIS 72 was the Command Module AGC software flown on Apollo 15, Apollo 16, and Apollo 17.
AURORA 85 was the Lunar Module AGC software for the unmanned LTA-8 ground tests.
AURORA 88 was AGC software used for checkout of the Lunar Module G&N system.

SHEPATIN was a branch of the software for investigating certain engineering concepts, but we're not sure exactly what those concepts were.  We know it had at least 6 revisions.  There were many of these side projects that we know little or nothing about, with names like MAMOUTH, LOCAVOID, NEWPRET, SDCDANCE, RADAR, LEADIN, COMPASS, and so on.
SUNBURST 120 was the Lunar Module AGC software flown in the unmanned Apollo 5 mission.
SUNDANCE 306 was the Lunar Module AGC software flown in the Apollo 9 mission.
SKYLARK 48 was the Command Module AGC software flown in the Skylab 2, Skylab 3, Skylab 4, and ASTP missions.
RETREAD was the very first Block II AGC program, from which all other Block II AGC programs eventually evolved.

SUNDIAL in general, and SUNDIAL E specifically, was AGC software used to check out Command Module G&N systems.  It was also the Command Module AGC software in the 4 manned but ground-based missions called 2TV-1.
SUNDISK 282 was the Command Module AGC software flown in the Apollo 7 mission.

ECLIPSE is the earliest-known AGC program.  It was for a Block I AGC.  The program is named for the fact that it was developed partly during a major solar eclipse in 1963.  Fun fact:  That eclipse occurred on July 20, 1963.
CORONA 261 was the Block I Command Module AGC software that flew in the unmanned AS-202 mission.
SOLARIUM 55 was the Block I Command Module AGC software that flew in the unmanned Apollo 4 and Apollo 6 missions.

SUNSPOT was the Block I Command Module AGC software that would have flown in the Apollo 1 mission and its two immediate follow-ups, had the Apollo 1 fire not caused all of those missions to be cancelled.  The software, nevertheless, was complete and ready to fly at the time of the trajedy.  The records are incomplete, however, and we cannot be sure that 247 was the specific SUNSPOT revision intended for Apollo 1.  However, it is the highest revision that we are aware of that was tested for that purpose.
AGS Flight Program 2 (FP2) was flown on the unmanned Apollo 5 mission.
AGS Flight Program 3 (FP3) was flown on the Apollo 9 mission.
AGS Flight Program 5 (FP5) was flown on the Apollo 10 mission.
AGS Flight Program 6 (FP6) was flown on the Apollo 11 and Apollo 12 missions.
AGS Flight Program 7 (FP7) was flown on the Apollo 13 and Apollo 14 missions.
AGS Flight Program 8 (FP8) was flown on the Apollo 15, Apollo 16, and Apollo 17 missions.
